European inflation has slipped in food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the sharp increase in the price of foodstuffs.
The increase in prices in November was higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, registering - after 2.6 percent of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced by the Union Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only gave as likely 3 percent - announced the Bloomberg.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, together with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least about two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is trapped 22: "there is to negotiate" on inflation so that it will not have to intervene later on on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, hit the 12-year record; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation was fired in the euro area as a result of the galloping food and energy prices.
Contributions to the wheat term increased by 88 per cent and soy quotas have also reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 per barrel of black gold last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 percent current to 2.5 percent, but by 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
Gallup anticipates a government crisis
After a long stagnation, by early December the support of the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its peak since 2002, while the Gallup had never before experienced such a low - 13 percent - level in the case of socialists.
The difference in the case of the safe voters of the parties - due to the strongest of the voters of the opposition - would mean more than two-thirds (71 percent) support against the support of one fifth for the socialists (20 percent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach the limit necessary to have a parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is about two percent.
Among the safe voters there are one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the lowest point - it has never been so high, 41 per cent the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 per cent believe that the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as next year is concerned, the majority of the population is experiencing the deterioration of the situation and only a tenth party expects improvement.
In December, 71 per cent of the respondents, higher than any previous Gallup survey, felt that the President of the Government was rather ill-functioning than well-functioning.
13 percent of the respondents trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of the respondents.
54 per cent of the population does not trust the Head of Government at all and 27 per cent do not trust the President of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced against the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the disturbances in October last year 35 per cent felt it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, this proportion is currently only 20 per cent, while the relative majority (33 per cent) believes that the only solution is the holding of new elections.
The interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 per cent of respondents to the question about participation answered that they would surely participate and another 20 per cent said that it is likely that they will participate.
Comparatively, in "a general election to be held this Sunday", only 55 per cent of the population would participate safely and another 15 per cent would believe that they would participate. Based on the current intentions of the voters, there is no doubt about the result of the popular consultation.
74 per cent of the population would disapprove of the payment of education rights, 79 per cent of the medical services and 84 per cent of hospital care.
If we observe these proportions only among the participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of education rights, payment for medical consultations and the payment of hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The average price increase of 16 per cent remained the hypermarkets of the Budaörs commercial gold triangle, with the difference that this year VAT has not been increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the commercial gold triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the newspaper Napi, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth much higher than the thousand HUFs.
As in December last year prices in food supermarkets had already been "disappeared", so there was no dramatic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is evidently frightening for consumers that what they could buy last year at a price well below the nine thousand HUFs, today they can't even do it for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of 10,000 HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10 573 HUF.
(in 2003 this basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a strong increase in turkey breast fillet, nut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed data from the Central Statistical Office, although in the Auchan we also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this shop that the price of the Coca-Cola with two-liter refillable bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in the Napi Auchan basket it was the most expensive, while Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, in relation to last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent the prices in the Napi basket.
Comparing the most expensive basket values of last year with the cheapest basket of this year, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between the cheapest of last year and the most expensive of this year has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during last year's Christmas prices the increase in VAT was felt.
Just this process was the one that destroyed trade, the supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of the change in prices on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of the movement of a product, it may lose an important benefit in the margin that fits the volume of sales.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, which the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF than the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only an 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, since the price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased by 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets more than 30 percent of the price of consumer goods of primary need grew.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the Central Statistical Office's figures: this office, in the case of some necessities, recorded a price increase of over 30 percent in the 12-month interval.
For example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of eggs.)
According to the Napi basket, in this latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product which was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, it was recorded, in the worst of cases only 10 percent of price increase.
According to all indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, which can impose the drastic price increase even to multinationals.
The hypermarkets do not complain in the commercial triangle of gold, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experience, most consumers in the three shops visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all products buy large quantities, taking preserved foods by pallets.
In the morning of Wednesday, large queues were formed in the three stores in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that inside the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because income is below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been reported in hospitals primarily due to the misuse of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene circumstances in hospitals, bed overcrowding and staff overload do not favor the control of infections - says the medical-chief department of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many hospitals, even disinfectants are saved.
A MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital early this year.
A victim of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital shortly after the infection with MRSA and no major surgical intervention has been performed since then because of the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10th of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance - said Karolina Böröcz, the head doctor of the department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded in hospitals, but no information is available.
Almost two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, namely Staphylococcus aureus, methicillin-oxacillin-resistant.
One third of humans carry on their nose the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) without causing any disease.
Infections produced by SA (e. g.: sore throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once the antibiotics are applied over or improperly, the bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become very resistant bacteria to antibiotics and quickly become infected in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause severe hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicemia in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened body, to the elderly or to people with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic Resistant
"These patients are isolated, nursing staff attends them in rubber gloves and masks and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalised patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but it is not even possible to avoid infection in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA's hospital infections in most cases, but current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of training and infection with multi-resistant pathogens - Karolina Böröcz says.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the patients with MRSA in their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, microbiological samples are not fashionable.
This fact is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases go out to the public when there are already visible MRSA infections in the patient - said the head doctor of the epidemiological center department.
The European Union is making strict commitments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological frameworks.
Antibiotic therapy should be used, i.e. microbiological tests should be performed to prevent resistance to drugs, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological samples are even less frequent in the case of travelling patients or in basic care - Karolina Böröcz said.
Saves with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, handwashing, the use of rubber gloves and masks is a very important role, but there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is infected by drop transmission and direct contact between individuals, but in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, one can also experience - Karolina Böröcz added - that in hospitals with less favourable economic conditions it is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate preventive measures are carried out, fewer infections of this kind are recorded or the infection of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Sickness Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fought against it.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
According to the data provided, MRSA infections appear to have a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative alcohol control of the police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report has been made on the case of the fatal accident caused by the 21st District Police Commander.
It may be ruled out the possibility that he had been drunk or in a state in which he had since resigned police commander of District XXII, who on Tuesday struck and caused the death of a transgender - reported Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Attorney General's Office of the Capital, after the expert report on the case had been prepared.
The expert report confirmed the result of primary alcohol control which had already found that the former police commander did not consume alcohol before putting himself behind the steering wheel.
The then chief of the police station in district XXII, on Tuesday with his particular vehicle as he doubled to the street Kossuth Lajos in district XXII, hit a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the area designated for pedestrians.
(This last fact, i.e. that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way by bending.)
The passerby lost his life after being hospitalized.
As a result, the district police leader resigned and applied for retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very moved by the case.
The case investigation is under the responsibility of the Budapest Investigation Office.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the outset collaborated with prosecutors responsible for the investigation.
EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
The Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and the Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements in Budapest for a total of EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and the environment infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget transport and environmental protection projects, to be made from the grant of cohesion funds, of which the parties had previously signed a credit agreement of EUR 100 million, the contract that they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit contract is also intended to finance the budget of educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective in Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million, the decision will be taken later in the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for EUR 50 million for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the project of innovations and research at the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the topic of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary completes with the EU the details of the Metro financing, they will again deal with the issue whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this will take place early in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the appropriations is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charge for keeping the loan available to the debtor.
