Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Foundor, expert-level meetings will end on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at ministers-level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are deliberating on the Bali Road Map, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
Discussions on the particulars between developing and industrialized countries are currently under way.
The United States has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate on accurate figures at the moment, although it tends to reach the agreement that, compared to the 1990 situation, by 2020, it decreases by 25 to 40 per cent the emission of greenhouse gases.
Another major theme of the conference is that if industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member steering board, probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF) - writes the "Piac é Profit".
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent to 2020, regardless of whether or not the "after-2012 agreement" will be signed, and is willing to commit to a reduction of even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to take commitments in accordance with their responsibilities and capacities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatories to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 per cent, within which 15 EU Member States committed to achieving 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent over the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will implement - notes the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
This is much at stake in Bali, since within two years the international long-term climate policy agreement will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force will be postponed until after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need of which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the UN international scientific association dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
In this way, emission reduction would be delayed and an increase of more than 2°C of the Earth's average temperature could not be prevented, since according to scientists, it would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish recordings on actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the general body of Kandahar operations, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings from the air force soldiers who have been loaded this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by over 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defence leaders" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Ministry of the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
The air force had originally uploaded the videos with recruitment goals, but in the view of the Ministry of Defence they also served to present to the public the true objective of the British army's presence abroad.
This kind of propaganda almost cost nothing compared to conventional recruitment television spots - told the BBC the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - but inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans have prepared a video game
The army is also concerned that, in addition to the anxiously edited and censored recordings, videos are also featured in the distributor, for example, about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers speak at most of the losses, although they do not present the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in actual operations have already been uploaded to the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
The Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with video game shooting, free downloadable, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly instead of the soldiers.
