Gathering the forces of the giant strike
The League Unions and the National Federation of Labour Commissions will constitute a strike commission on Friday to coordinate the Monday strike that will last indefinitely.
On Saturday a protest rally will be held, while on Monday - the day on which the final vote on the public health law will be held - the unemployment will begin.
This action will certainly cause great difficulties in transport, as rail transit will be stopped completely and workers of the Collective Transport Company in Budapest will also be on strike by 13 hours.
On Friday afternoon, the League Unions will report on the details of their Monday strike, which will be held jointly with the National Federation of Labour Commissions.
The strike commission of the LIGA and the National Trade Union of Machines will also be set up to coordinate the actions of Monday.
On Saturday a protest rally will be held, while on Monday the participating unions will pronounce on strike for an indefinite time, if no agreement is reached with the government.
This means that, on the day of the parliamentary vote on the public health law, they did not report on the date of the end of the strike.
If the National Assembly disapproves of the public health law, the unions will immediately withdraw their appeal to the strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on the future.
On the basis of the agenda of Monday of the National Assembly, it is also possible that only public health law may be voted on at very late hours of the night, or at best near midnight.
As a result of the strike to be launched on Monday, there will have to be significant difficulties in transport: railways will cease to work indefinitely, in the morning a part of the collective transport of Budapest and more than half of the inter-urban bus transport of the Volan companies may be stopped.
At the same time, at many points in the country, half of the roads will be closed.
Numerous trade unions and civil organizations have joined the strike, their names are constantly updated on the League's website.
Some unions announced their strike indefinitely, others for a defined time.
Until Thursday evening the State Railway and the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) were unable to reach an agreement even on minimum services, but as Christmas parties approached, more and more people were traveling on the trains.
According to information received so far, from the beginning of the day until 1 p.m. workers from the Collective Transport Company in Budapest will be on strike, Budapest airports from 7 to 9 a.m., will hold a four-hour strike at the Liga Electrical Industry and Thermal Energy Unions, the Educators' Unions will call for a 2 p.m. strike and the Democratic Union of Educators from 2 to 8 hours.
The Hungarian Association of Physicians will take a national strike at alternative times and the Democratic Union of Workers of the Health and Social Sector (SDTSSS) which forms part of the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is that the government withdraws its proposal on public health reform and submits a new conception to a social debate.
The second demand is to gradually introduce the new form of pension calculation which will enter into force next year.
The third is to ensure, even before 2010, that early pensions may be allowed to enter the system.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) which is part of the League Unions, do not accept the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport on the railway side lines and expect another different proposal.
Political Capital[b1]: In the country the risk by the Hungarian Guard is increased
According to the Risk Analysis Division (Risk Analysis Division) of the Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, constituted in August this year with the support of the Movement by a Better Hungary, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region from a number of points of view.
In the company's "risk warning" it is written: in relation to the Hungarian Guard's activity the greatest political risk is that "with the worsening of the ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Gypsy population of Hungary, even in the short term violent ethnic clashes may occur".
The main reason for this is that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy is probably the provocation of such an event - added the representative of the Research Institute.
They stated that this was due to one of the main shortcomings of the protagonists of Hungarian political life: "the protagonists of public life gave public debate of the Roma problem to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who were able to base their political strategy on the differences between Roma and Hungarians".
This exacerbates the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of the outbreak of violent conflicts - they estimate.
Moreover, according to the research institute, the activity of the National Guard, as a result of the great attention of the national and international average, "has significantly deteriorated Hungary's image abroad, especially in terms of the country's stability and democratic development".
They remind us that since the fall of 2006 there has been increasing publicity and momentum for the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary and that since the summer of 2007 there have been numerous organizations that have self-defended "national self-defence associations" in the country.
"The common feature of these groups is that they self-definite themselves as civil organizations, while openly proclaiming the training of their members for the defence - even armed - (civil defense, national defence, defense of the public order), alluding to the ineptitudes of the police, the army, that is the state" - they add.
