After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the destinations of 17.5 million victims of the Hitlerian regime, are in free access.
The 47 million file documents, stored over 27 km of shelves to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far available only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of an old victim or his rights.
The eleven States in charge of their management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
