The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war in a practical way: to find the deported or subjected to compulsory work and, if necessary, to provide proof of their detention, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
