In parallel with its parliamentary procedure, which ended today with the Congress's vote on the amendments incorporated into the draft in the Senate, the Government has submitted to the public hearing the regulations that will develop the new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best rules in order to ensure investor protection and to regulate the activity of entities in detail to ensure that markets function efficiently.
The Mifid, which amends the Value Market Act, involves the modernisation of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and encourages cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new regulation will provide financial advisory services to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and will create a new type of financial service signatures (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFIs), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
It also expands the number of systems for the implementation of financial instrument operations, so that regulated secondary markets are added to multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also obliges investment service companies to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management forms on the market and requires them to keep a record of all operations they carry out, to facilitate supervision by CNMV.
In its passage through the Congress's Economy Commission, several amendments were incorporated, among which it highlights that debt securities are considered as a "complex" financial instrument given its high investor risk, which has been demonstrated by the US high-risk mortgage debt (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delimit the functions that graduates can perform in Economics and Business 30 years after the Royal Decree delimiting the professional functions reserved for economists was adopted in 1977.
For its part, the Senate incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as that of the mediator, who will work for others, will not require the authorization of the CNMV and will be able to provide its services for the marketing of products and the collection of customers to different investment firms at the same time.
