Venus: twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that has not yet been raised. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and whirlpools in the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades now, researchers had suspected that there could be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new tests: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays run from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, tells Cris Russell of California University in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, the rays caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, would have given rise to amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not so: if one day there would be life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface reinstate temperatures of 500°C, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Possibly, Venus is a "diabolic" twin of the Earth, but it remains a twin," said Russell.
The main objective of the mission "Venus Express" is to answer the question why Venus, so much like the Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, just for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus' research.
The latest results of the research to be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to researchers' opinion, stress not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more characteristics common to the Earth than we had assumed," the ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, the researchers discovered in the South Polar Region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon reminds the wind flows in the high atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost so large.
This planet also called the star of dawn or the star of evening orbits around the Sun nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day in Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and with its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars is not much like Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets, water had been packed, which on Earth remained in the oceans, but in Venus it dissociated into the universe.
While carbon dioxide on Earth had become carbon stones, Venus is the largest part of the atmosphere.
